package::function()

ggplot(data = mpg)+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))

ggplot() creates the coordinate system. the argument it accepts is the dataset. You can then add layers onto it to change it around

ggplot(data = mpg)

geom_point adds a layer of points. It always has a mapping argument paired with aes(). x and y variables state which variables should go along the axis.

generically the code is ### ggplot(data = )+ (mapping = aes())

There are 234 rows, with 11 columns. drv is for front wheel, back wheel, or 4 wheel drive.

The class vs drv could still be a useful plot. It simply represents the drive options avalible in the sample. Like something you might see in consumer reports.

ggplot(data = mpg)+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = cyl, y = hwy))

ggplot(data = mpg)+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = class, y = drv))

Plot is for graphing Geometry is the type of graph Aesthetics are the visual representations on the graph. This determines aspects like color, size, or shape. Different data types can be distinguished this way.

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = class))

ggplot(data = mpg)+
  geom_point(mapping =aes(x = displ, y = hwy, size = class))
## Warning: Using size for a discrete variable is not advised.

ggplot(data = mpg)+
  geom_point(mapping =aes(x = displ, y = hwy, alpha = class))
## Warning: Using alpha for a discrete variable is not advised.

ggplot(data = mpg)+
  geom_point(mapping =aes(x = displ, y = hwy, shape = class))
## Warning: The shape palette can deal with a maximum of 6 discrete values
## because more than 6 becomes difficult to discriminate; you have 7.
## Consider specifying shapes manually if you must have them.
## Warning: Removed 62 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

ggplot(data = mpg)+

## Facets you can split categorical data into separate subplots called a facet

ggplot(data = mpg)+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y= hwy)) +
  facet_wrap(~ cty, nrow = 2)

ggplot(data = mpg)+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y= hwy)) +
  facet_grid(drv ~ cyl)

ggplot(data = mpg)+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y= hwy)) +
  facet_grid(. ~ cyl)

3.5.1 1. It breaks the plot up and makes what looks like a trend across the graphs. 2. It means there is no engines of that many cylinders with that type of drive system. 3. The first one includes a subplot with drive systems, the second cylinders. The period means to not plot anything in that axis for additional facet subplots. 4. The advantage to using facets is that it makes trends within a specific sub-plot more easily viewable. The disadvantage is that it becomes more difficult to view connections with the rest of the data. If the data set is large enough the points might look random until split up. 5.nrow and ncol determine the number of rows and columns.Labeller, each output line displayed as one separate line in the strip label. 6. Facet grid will show graphs even if there is no data for them, while facet wrap will display only the ones that have a graph.

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))+
  facet_grid(drv ~ .)

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))+
  facet_wrap(drv ~ .)

ggplot(data = mpg)+
  geom_point(mapping = aes (x = displ, y = hwy))

ggplot(data = mpg)+
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes (x = displ, y = hwy))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(data = mpg)+
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes (x = displ, y = hwy, color = drv, linetype = drv),show.legend = FALSE)+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y =hwy, color = drv))

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x =displ, y=hwy, color =drv))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

3. This will hide the legend. Sometimes the legend is redundant based on the labels. 4. This displays the confidence interval. 5. They will look the same, you can reduce duplicate data by placing the aes in ggplot 6.

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x=displ, y=hwy, linetype = "solid"))+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(),color="black")+
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE, mapping = aes(group=drv))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x=displ, y=hwy))+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(),color="black")+
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x=displ, y=hwy, color= drv))+
  geom_point(mapping = aes())+
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x=displ, y=hwy,color = drv))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE, color = "blue")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x=displ, y=hwy))+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color=drv))+
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE, mapping = aes(linetype = drv))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'
